20","1250":"1250","abt 1220":"circa 1220","1170":"1170","Bewley, Louth, Ireland":"County Kilkenny, Ierland"},"en":{"abt 1220–Deceased":"about 1220–Deceased","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1244–1279":"1244–1279","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","1279":"1279","1244":"1244","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","abt 1220":"about 1220","1170":"1170","Bewley, Louth, Ireland":"County Kilkenny, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Plunkett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from a metathesized form of Plouquenet in Ille-et-Villaine, Brittany, so named from Breton <i>plou</i> ‘parish’ (from Latin <i>plebs</i> ‘people’) + <i>Guenec</i>, the personal name (a diminutive of <i>guen</i> ‘white’) of a somewhat obscure saint. As an Irish name, it has been Gaelicized as <b>Pluincéid</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Plunket","meanings":["English (northern) and Irish: variant of   Plunkett  ."]}]},{"name":"Patrick","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name of the apostle and patron saint of Ireland (  <i>c.</i>389–461 ), Gaelic <i>Pádraig</i>. He was a Christian Briton and a Roman citizen, who as a young man was captured and enslaved by raiders from Ireland. He escaped and went to Gaul before returning home to Britain. In about  419  he felt a call to do missionary work in Ireland. He studied for twelve years at Auxerre, and in  432  returned to Ireland. For the rest of his life it is difficult to distinguish fact from fiction. He apparently went to the court of the high kings at Tara and made some converts there; then he travelled around Ireland making further converts until about  445 , when he established his archiepiscopal see at Armagh. By the time of his death almost the whole of Ireland is said to have been converted to Christianity. He is also credited with codifying the laws of Ireland. In his Latin autobiography, as well as in later tradition, his name appears as <i>Patricius</i> ‘patrician’ (i.e. belonging to the Roman senatorial or noble class), but this may actually represent a Latinized form of some lost Celtic (British) name. In Ireland in particular, it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Patrick Plunkett was born about 1220, in County Kilkenny, Ireland as the son of Richard Plunkett , 1st Lord of Louth. He had at least 2 sons."},"et":{"abt 1220–Deceased":"umbes 1220–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1244–1279":"1244–1279","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1279":"1279","1244":"1244","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1170":"1170","Bewley, Louth, Ireland":"County Kilkenny, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"abt 1220–Deceased":"noin 1220–Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1244–1279":"1244–1279","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1279":"1279","1244":"1244","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","abt 1220":"noin 1220","1170":"1170","Bewley, Louth, Ireland":"County Kilkenny, Irlanti"},"fr":{"abt 1220–Deceased":"environ 1220–Décédé","1220–Male":"1220–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1244–1279":"1244–1279","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1170–Male":"1170–Décédé","1279":"1279","1244":"1244","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","abt 1220":"environ 1220","1170":"1170","Bewley, Louth, Ireland":"County Kilkenny, Irlande","lifeSummary":"Patrick Plunkett est né environ 1220, à County Kilkenny, Irlande, fils de Richard Plunkett , 1st Lord of Louth. Il a eu au moins 2 fils."},"de":{"abt 1220–Deceased":"um 1220–Verstorben","1220–Male":"1220–Verstorben","–Male":"Verstorben","1244–1279":"1244–1279","1250–Male":"1250–Verstorben","1170–Male":"1170–Verstorben","1279":"1279","1244":"1244","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","abt 1220":"um 1220","1170":"1170","Bewley, Louth, Ireland":"County Kilkenny, Irland","lifeSummary":"Patrick